From this, we can take the earnings per share (EPS) by dividing the current earnings by the new number of outstanding shares. This can be done using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EPS}&=\dfrac{\text{Earnings per share} \times \text{Original number of outstanding shares}}{\text{New number of outstanding shares}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get an EPS value of:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EPS}&=\dfrac{\$1.89 \times 2,000}{1,727}\\[15 pt]
&=\$2.19
\end{aligned}$$

The earnings per share if the company repurchases shares is $\$2.19$ which is higher compared to issuing new shares.
